## ✅ Lesson 1 — How APIs are used in **Hospital Patient Monitoring Systems (HPM)**

You are working on a **Philips Hospital Patient Monitoring System Support Tool**, so before learning API automation, you must understand **how APIs exist inside real hospital software**.

In real healthcare products, API is not theory — it connects:

* UI ↔ Backend
* Backend ↔ Database
* Backend ↔ Device
* Tool ↔ Monitor hardware
* Tool ↔ Hospital network
* Tool ↔ User roles

This is exactly the type of system used in **Philips / Siemens / GE Healthcare**.

---

## 🏥 1. What is a Hospital Patient Monitoring System (HPM)

A Patient Monitoring System is used in:

* ICU
* Operation Theater
* Emergency
* Ward monitoring
* Central monitoring station

It monitors:

* Heart rate
* SPO2
* ECG
* Blood pressure
* Temperature
* Respiration

And sends data to:

* Monitor screen
* Central station
* Support tool
* Database
* Remote service tool

Your **Support Tool** is used by:

* Field Service Engineer
* R&D
* Admin
* Clinical user
* Normal user

---

## 🧩 2. Real Architecture of HPM System

Typical architecture in Philips-like systems:

```
Monitor Device  →  Backend Service  →  Database
                       ↓
                 API Layer
                       ↓
                Support Tool UI (WPF)
```

or

```
UI → API → Service → DB
UI → API → Device
UI → API → Auth Server
```

So when user clicks button in UI → API call happens.

---

## 🔹 Example from your Support Tool

User clicks:

```
Login
```

Internally:

```
UI → API → /login → backend → DB → response → UI
```

User clicks:

```
Enumerator screen
```

Internally:

```
UI → API → /devices/list → backend → device service → response
```

User connects cable:

```
UI → API → /connectDevice
```

User role changes:

```
UI → API → /getFeaturesByRole
```

So every feature = API call

